The Trojan Horse of Europe
BERKELEY – Europe will have no choice but to bail out Greece.
Emergency funds will have to be provided.
Conditions will have to be attached.
The Greek government will make the usual promises.
This should allow the Greek government to service its debt.
Markets will calm down.
The long-term consequences will not be prohibitive, but there will be problems ahead.
Some will say that the fatal mistake was allowing Greece to adopt the euro in the first place.
It was nevertheless already evident that the country was not ready.
Its budgetary policy was already out of control when it joined the monetary union in 2001 and its unions were already pushing for Greek wages to align with those practiced in Europe, despite lagging productivity.
But this response is too simplistic, as such signs of dysfunction are not limited to Greece.
Spain, with a 20% unemployment rate and abyssal budget deficits, sees Greece as a reflection of its own future.
And if that is not the case, the markets will take care of it.
Portugal and Italy are doing a bit better.
These countries, just like Greece, must face significant budget cuts.
Like Greece, they cannot devalue their currency to boost exports.
Like Greece, they must face a deep recession.
Like Greece, they will be tempted to seek aid.
All of this raises a single question: wasn't the real mistake creating the euro?
Given that I was one of the few Americans to support the idea of a European currency, you might be entitled to ask: are you reconsidering your initial position?
My answer is no, creating the euro was not a mistake, but it could well become one.
The Greek crisis shows that Europe is only halfway along the path to a viable monetary union.
If it does nothing, the next crisis could well make this one seem like a walk in the park.
If Europe wants to complete its monetary union, it will need to create its own emergency financing mechanism.
Today, members of the Union can only help Greece by bypassing the regulations that prevent them from granting a loan except in the case of natural disasters or circumstances beyond a country's control.
This exacerbates uncertainty.
When European leaders provide aid, public opinions and markets tend to question their honesty.
If the problems stem from the Lisbon Treaty, then it needs to be amended.
Furthermore, aid should not be granted only under certain conditions, but should be accompanied by temporary national budget control by a committee of "experts" appointed by the European Union.
History shows that simple promises made by beneficiary countries are not enough.
Of course, countries subjected to such measures will express their indignation.
But, no one forces them to accept this money.
Moral considerations?
Here is your solution.
Note that this would be a much more effective disciplinary mechanism than the defunct Stability and Growth Pact.
One could also ask the following question: how would Californians react if their state temporarily placed its budget in the hands of an expert specifically appointed by the administration of President Barack Obama?
In fact, it would not bother them that much.
The expert would not be a native Californian, but an American.
Public opinion would understand that he would act in the interest of the Californian state as well as in that of the country.
The fact that California sends representatives to Washington, from which this expert's orders would emanate, would reassure them.
Europeans do not do this kind of thing because they first and foremost see themselves as Greeks and Germans.
They do not interfere with the "sovereign prerogatives" of other member states.
Germany is particularly reluctant given its history during World War II, especially in Greece.
If Europe really wants to achieve its monetary union, it will have to overcome its past.
This union implies not only stronger economic ties, but also closer political ties.
Those who have a solid emergency aid mechanism will really have to account for it.
They will have to answer to a strong European Parliament.
The electorate of German Chancellor Angela Merkel hates this kind of rescue because they well know who will be responsible for it.
Germans oppose anything that resembles European political integration.
But Germany has its share of responsibility in this crisis.
It wanted a central bank incredibly independent and not obliged to account for its actions, but today it has adopted an excessively restrictive monetary policy, thereby critically worsening the situation of the PIIGS (Portugal, Ireland, Italy, Greece, and Spain).
Its huge current account surpluses further aggravate their situation.
Moreover, its fiscal stimulus measures have not been sufficient to support the European economy.
Germany has significantly benefited from the creation of the euro.
She should do the same.
She should encourage the creation of an emergency loan facility, as well as political integration to make it possible.
She must provide more budgetary support.
Isn't she best placed to push for a more accountable European Central Bank?
The Greek crisis could be the Trojan horse that leads Europe toward a more advanced political integration.
One can only hope.
